      "writtenOn": "2016-11-14T14:43:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Right, although the \"no data\" state is actually data showing the last trigger was at the time of the last restart.\n\nCould we do the following at startup?\n 1. Scan the JobSpecs at HEAD and find any with triggers specified.\n 2. Map those triggers to a time range that we expect to contain the most recent run for that trigger. (Unfortunately this means that the trigger times are specified in multiple places.)\n 3. Scan the DB for matching Jobs.\n 4. Set the metric to an appropriate value based on whether a Job was found and it succeeded.",
      "parentUuid": "eb935fd8_ddf41eb4",
      "revId": "33da49816a65b3307e7253b622b967654af45419",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "eb935fd8_9c260f2e",
        "filename": "task_scheduler/go/scheduling/periodic.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 35,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-11-14T15:15:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t really want to depend on Jobs in the DB to determine whether the triggering is working; we may remove job specs for a given trigger, or add a new one, and we may get false negatives or positives.\n\nAlternative suggestion:  Change the various triggers to use a fixed subdirectory and write a TRIGGER file there, eg:\n\n/workdir/periodic-job-trigger/nightly/TRIGGER\n\nThen we can enumerate the directories to obtain the list of all trigger names.  That\u0027d also allow us to write a \"last-trigger-time\" file for each trigger, which we could read on startup to properly initialize the livenesses.  Really, we could just use a single last-trigger.json file containing a map for all triggers.\n\nThoughts?",
      "parentUuid": "eb935fd8_41d82437",
      "revId": "33da49816a65b3307e7253b622b967654af45419",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
